Function for replacing outliers

replaceoutliers <- function(x){
  qntile <- quantile(x,probs=c(0.25,0.75))
  caps <-quantile(x,probs=c(0.10,0.90))
  H <- 1.5*IQR(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  x[x<(qntile[1]-H)] <-caps[1]
  x[x>(qntile[2]+H)] <-caps[2]
  return(x)
}

Replace outlier

6) Try to assess predictive accuracy using other metrics:

y    = bikeshare$cnt
yhat = predict(bs4)
n    = length(y)
p    = 8 #number of predictors in the model, besides the intercept

RSS: residual sum of squares

RSS = sum((y-yhat)^2)
RSS
## [1] 491115674

note relation to r-squared

1-RSS/sum((y-mean(y))^2)
## [1] 0.8207303

RSE: residual standard error

sqrt(RSS/(n-p-1))
## [1] 824.7519

MSE: mean squared error

mean(sum((y-yhat)^2))
## [1] 491115674

RMSE: root mean squared error

sqrt(mean(sum((y-yhat)^2)))
## [1] 22161.13

Predictions - bs5log

y    = log(bikeshare$cnt)

note relation to r-squared

MSE: mean squared error

RMSE: root mean squared error

## [1] 7.752571

We can see that bs5log is better than bs4 because its RSS is smaller than that of bs4. Besides, and r-square of bs5log just slightly smaller than bs4s. The inference is that it would be better if we choose bs5log.
